# 🚢 Titanic Survival Prediction

A complete Data Science project implementing the full ML pipeline: **Data Loading → EDA → Cleaning → Visualization → Feature Engineering → Model Building → Evaluation**

## 📋 Project Overview

This project analyzes the Titanic dataset and builds a machine learning model to predict passenger survival using **Logistic Regression**. Achieves ~80% accuracy.

## 🎯 Objectives

- Understand the complete data science workflow
- Apply data preprocessing and feature engineering techniques
- Build and evaluate a classification model
- Visualize insights from the data

## 🛠️ Technologies Used

- **Python 3.10+**
- **Libraries**: pandas, numpy, matplotlib, seaborn, scikit-learn

## 📂 Project Structure

```
titanic-survival-prediction/
│
├── Titanic_Survival_Prediction.ipynb   # Main Jupyter notebook
├── README.md                             # Project documentation
└── requirements.txt                      # Python dependencies
```

## 🚀 How to Run

### Option 1: Google Colab (Recommended - No Setup Required)

1. Go to [Google Colab](https://colab.research.google.com)
2. File → Upload notebook → select `Titanic_Survival_Prediction.ipynb`
3. Runtime → Run all (`Ctrl+F9`)

### Option 2: Local Setup

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/titanic-survival-prediction.git
cd titanic-survival-prediction

# Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# Launch Jupyter Notebook
jupyter notebook Titanic_Survival_Prediction.ipynb
```

## 📊 What's Inside

| Step | Description |
|------|-------------|
| **0** | Import all required libraries |
| **1** | Load Titanic dataset from web (no manual download) |
| **2** | Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) - shape, missing values, survival rate |
| **3** | Data Cleaning - handle nulls, drop irrelevant columns, encode categories |
| **4** | Data Visualization - 6 charts (survival by gender, class, age, fare, heatmap) |
| **5** | Feature Engineering - create FamilySize and IsAlone features |
| **6** | Model Building - Logistic Regression with 80/20 split |
| **7** | Evaluation - Accuracy, Confusion Matrix, Classification Report, Feature Importance |
| **8** | Custom Prediction - Test with your own passenger data |

## 📈 Results

- **Accuracy**: ~80%
- **Key Insights**:
  - Women had significantly higher survival rates than men
  - 1st class passengers had better survival odds
  - Children were more likely to survive
  - Higher fares correlated with survival
  - Travelling alone reduced survival chances

## 🔍 Features Used

- Pclass (Passenger Class)
- Sex
- Age
- Fare
- FamilySize (engineered)
- IsAlone (engineered)
- Embarked (port of embarkation)

## 📝 Key Learnings

- Data preprocessing and handling missing values
- Feature engineering to create meaningful predictors
- Data visualization for insights
- Building and evaluating classification models
- Interpreting model coefficients

